[normal]What is a secure track and trace system?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]5.    
[normal]A secure track and trace system 
[normal]begins by securely marking a unit of product (e.g. a pack of cigarettes) and
[normal] assigning 
[normal]to 
[normal]it a unique identity which is stored in a government owned and controlled database
[normal].
[normal] This can be done in such a way as to provide a 
[normal]fully reliable 
[normal]test of authenticity and to be information rich (linked to data about e.g. product 
[normal]type
[normal], time and place of manufacture, intended market of sale
[normal] et al
[normal]). The unique identity 
[normal]and the database are 
[normal]the building block
[normal]s
[normal] of a tracking capability which allows the unit to be followed throughout the supply chain -
[normal] if required 
[normal]up 
[normal]to 
[normal]the point of sale to the consumer. 
[normal] 
[normal]They also provide
[normal] the means to tra
[normal]ce backwards 
[normal]in real-time 
[normal]to point of origin
[normal]/manufacture
[normal] 
[normal]etc
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]at anytime during the product lifecycle.
[normal] 
[normal]A properly secure system is essential to meet the challenge of ever more sophisticated organised crime groups.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The key components[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.    
[normal]The 
[normal]quality of the marking system is key[bold]. 
[normal]Marks that are properly secure and well-designed
[normal] to meet the needs of the different stakeholders
[normal], such as those recommended by SICPA, 
[normal]are easy to use, 
[normal]make counterfeiting virtually impossible
[normal] and provide information that enables enforcement
[normal]. 
[normal]We assess that the current 
[normal]UK
[normal] protection system (which 
[normal]we understand 
[normal]combines a
[normal]n easy-to-copy black ink 
[normal]‘
[normal]UK
[normal] tax paid’ mark combined with a material
[normal]-based
[normal] feature on the tear tape) to be 
[normal]relatively 
[normal]weak. 
[normal]Moreover 
[normal]illicit cigarettes in 
[normal]h
[normal]igh quality counterf
[normal]eited packaging are
[normal] difficult 
[normal]for enforcers 
[normal]to identify in real-time and need to be verified by manufacturers
[normal],
[normal] which 
[normal]can cause
[normal] inconvenience and delay
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.    
[normal]SICPA 
[normal]recommends 
[normal]a 
[normal]multi-layered approach combining material-based [bold]security [bold]features[bold] (security inks which are both visible and invisible)
[normal],
[normal] [bold]IT security[bold] features[bold] (2D secure matrix, visible and/or invisible)
[normal] and 
[normal]forensic features[bold].  
[normal]Secure o
[normal]vert features can be seen by consumers thus encouraging good citizenship; additional semi-covert features can be made available to e.g. retailers so they can protect themselves from unscrupulous suppliers; covert features can be verified by enforcers using bespoke checking equipment and used as evidence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.    
[normal]Both domestically produced 
[normal](including for export if required) 
[normal]and imported product can be marked
[normal],
[normal] but by definition it is only possible to mark product which is produced in a
[normal] declared/leg
[normal]itimate manufacturing facility
[normal] and/or
[normal] legitimately imported
[normal]. This does not mean (as some manuf
[normal]acturers might claim) that the
[normal] 
[normal]implementation of such a system ha
[normal]s 
[normal]no impact on the black and grey
[normal] markets
[normal] (where product moves between illegitimate and legitimate channels)
[normal]. Illegal product (i.e. produced illegally such as ‘illicit whites’ or illegal by 
[normal]virtue of being non-tax paid) would be
[normal] immediately identifiable
[normal] to all stakeholders
[normal] by the absence of the appropriate secure mark. 
[normal]Checks by enforcers 
[normal](linked back in real-time to the national database
[normal] and able to share with and interact with other government databases
[normal]) 
[normal]produce data not only to answer the question ‘
[normal]is this genuine or not
[normal]?
[normal]’ but 
[normal]to 
[normal]other 
[normal]enquiries such as
[normal] ‘
[normal]I
[normal]s this supposed to be coming here
[normal]?’
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]‘W
[normal]hat
[normal] tax
[normal] has 
[normal]been paid
[normal]?
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Business intelligence[bold]&#xa0;[bold]9.    
[normal]Techniques for e
[normal]xploit
[normal]ing data are progressing every day
[normal] and
[normal],
[normal] as more data is collected over-time
[normal],
[normal] become ever more powerful
[normal]. Data analysis and automated comparison of different data sets can identify patterns and anomalies which allow enforcers to make interventions against targets that would otherwise not have been spotted
[normal] and to identify changes in criminal behaviours. It also allows performance management of enforcer interventions (e.g. by locality or type) 
[normal]clarifying 
[normal]which 
[normal]interventions 
[normal]worked best.
