[normal]International agreements[bold]&#xa0;[bold]10.    
[normal]The 
[normal]UK
[normal] was an adopting party to the Protocol of the WHO 
[normal]FCTC
[normal] to 
[normal]‘
[normal]Eliminate the Illicit Trade in Tobacco 
[normal]P
[normal]roducts
[normal]’
[normal] in 
[normal]Seoul
[normal] in November 2012. 
[normal]As on so many topics where the 
[normal]UK
[normal] has taken the lead, what the 
[normal]UK
[normal] does in relation to the Protocol will be watched by other countries and followed by them.
[normal] Much of the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s problem has its origin overseas
[normal] (‘upstream’)
[normal] and proper implementation in these countries would positively impact on the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.    
[normal]The Protocol recognises the crucial 
[normal]global 
[normal]dimension of the illicit trade in tobacco products
[normal] and the need to ensure international co-operation and joint working
[normal]. Among the measures agreed is
[normal],
[normal] in
[normal] A
[normal]rticle 8 of the Protocol
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the requirement to implement national track and trace systems which are globally inter-operable[bold]. The Protocol foresees a five year period after coming into force for compliant national systems to be in place. 
[normal]In order to maximise value for money and longevity it 
[normal]is import
[normal]ant that any system foreseen in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] take
[normal]s
[normal] full account of the 
[normal]provisions
[normal] of the Protocol
[normal], which includes the requirement that any system be 
[normal]fully controlled by government and independent of the tobacco manufacturers[bold].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12.    
[normal]Having followed the process of negotiation with care and adapted our R
[normal]esearch
[normal] and D
[normal]evelopment
[normal] programme to take account of it, we are conscious that i
[normal]mplementing the spirit as well as the letter of the Protocol in an efficient way will not be a straight forward exercise e.g. it requires accurate aggregation (linking 
[normal]a 
[normal]single unit to higher level packaging i
[normal].
[normal]e
[normal].
[normal] a pack of cigarettes to 
[normal]its carton
[normal], and a carton
[normal] to its mastercase et al
[normal]) which requires high-level technical and engineering expertise as well as advanced IT
[normal]. In this area, as in others, SICPA is a patent holder.
